  "text": ", this amounts to a statement that the analysis is wellbehaved on the 0 double space of Mazzeo-Melrose [CITATION_1] when the smooth structure is given by the boundary defining function √ x. This is a somewhat complicated space with a non-commutative normal operator at infinity; there's a reduced normal operator after a partial Fourier transform and rescaling which is a b-scattering (or Bessel) type pseudodifferential operator on a half-line. This is the reason for using our sharper cutoff, which puts us into the more amenable setting of Melrose's scattering calculus, as described above.",
